🧱 IMPLEMENTATION ROADMAP (Production Style)

We split into 8 Major Stages.
Each stage builds on the previous.

You do NOT skip stages.

🟢 STAGE 0 — Foundation Setup

Goal: Clean project structure + tooling.

0.1 Initialize project

go mod init

folder structure

internal vs cmd separation

0.2 Add:

structured logging

config loader (env based)

basic HTTP server

graceful shutdown

No security yet. Just clean foundation.

Stage 0.5 — Dockerization Layer (before Auth)

This is where Docker comes in.

You:

Write multi-stage Dockerfile

Add docker-compose

Add postgres + minio containers

Ensure networking is internal

Ensure non-root container

Ensure resource limits

Ensure image scanning works


🟢 STAGE 1 — Authentication (AuthN at Gateway)

Goal: Establish identity boundary.

1.1 Define SecurityContext struct
1.2 Implement JWT validation:

signature check

expiry check

issuer validation

audience validation

1.3 Build Auth middleware:

extract Bearer token

validate

extract user_id

generate request_id

inject SecurityContext

1.4 Reject unauthenticated requests (401)

Invariant enforced:

No request reaches business logic without identity.

🟢 STAGE 2 — Tenant Resolution

Goal: Establish tenant boundary.

2.1 Design user-tenant mapping table
2.2 Resolve tenant from:

header OR

token claim OR

DB lookup

2.3 Inject tenant_id into SecurityContext
2.4 Enforce:

If user not member of tenant → 403

Invariant enforced:

Tenant context is server-resolved, never client-trusted.

🟢 STAGE 3 — Authorization Service (AuthZ Core)

Goal: Centralize permission decisions.

3.1 Define action model:

project.create

project.read

project.update

project.delete

3.2 Define role → permissions mapping
3.3 Implement AuthZ service (in-memory first)
3.4 Deny by default
3.5 gRPC optional (later)

Invariant enforced:

No mutation without explicit allow.

🟢 STAGE 4 — Project Service (With Tenant Isolation)

Goal: First real data-backed service.

4.1 Setup PostgreSQL
4.2 Define schema with tenant_id everywhere
4.3 Create repository layer:

All queries require tenant_id

No raw SQL in handlers

4.4 Implement:

Create project

Get project

Update project

Delete project

4.5 Insert AuthZ call:

After load, before mutation

4.6 Enforce:

Return 404 for cross-tenant

Invariant enforced:

Tenant isolation + AuthZ before mutation.

🟢 STAGE 5 — Database Hardening (RLS)

Goal: Defense in depth.

5.1 Enable PostgreSQL Row Level Security
5.2 Define tenant-based policy
5.3 Set tenant context per request
5.4 Test bypass attempts

Invariant enforced:

Even if code forgets tenant filter, DB blocks it.

🟢 STAGE 6 — File Service (Object Storage)

Goal: Secure file handling.

6.1 Setup MinIO
6.2 Design object key format:

tenant/{tenant_id}/project/{project_id}/file/{file_id}

6.3 Enforce:

Server-generated object keys

File size limit

MIME type validation

Streaming upload

6.4 AuthZ before file mutation

Invariant enforced:

File operations scoped to tenant + project.

🟢 STAGE 7 — Audit Service

Goal: Security visibility.

7.1 Create audit table (append-only)
7.2 Emit audit after successful mutation
7.3 Include:

actor

tenant

action

resource

request_id

7.4 Protect:

No update/delete on audit table

Invariant enforced:

Every sensitive action is traceable.

🟢 STAGE 8 — CI/CD + Supply Chain Security

Goal: Secure the build system.

8.1 Add:

govulncheck

trivy

dependency pinning

8.2 Block build on vulnerability
8.3 Secrets via environment only
8.4 Signed builds (optional advanced)

Invariant enforced:

Build pipeline cannot silently introduce vulnerabilities.

🟢 STAGE 9 — Abuse Case Testing

Goal: Validate threat model.

Manually attempt:

IDOR

Cross-tenant access

Role escalation

Token misuse

Missing authz bypass

Large file upload DoS

Fix what breaks.

🟢 STAGE 10 — Hardening & Observability

Goal: Production readiness mindset.

Rate limiting

Structured logging

Alerting hooks

Security event classification

Metrics per tenant

